[2026-03-13T20:00:03Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01ED6zjpgeJe8tVcXB4X9C6s","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NFcaMEBp3V6wgEaJ7avfjn","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":18487,"cache_read_input_tokens":15370,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":18487,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01X39tUhxFjzAhiJaof3xvLs","session_id":"80e1ce2e-a764-409e-b43f-733763e5218d","uuid":"01d98586-427d-4f33-a24b-f980066a7103"}
[2026-03-13T20:00:03Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NFcaMEBp3V6wgEaJ7avfjn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Additionally, `host.cloche` may define a **`release-task`** utility workflow. This is\n    28→not part of the automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n    29→web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. Receives\n    30→`CLOCHE_TASK_ID` for the task to release.\n    31→\n    32→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    33→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    34→\n    35→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    36→object with the following fields:\n    37→\n    38→| Field | Required | Description |\n    39→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    40→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    41→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    42→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    43→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    44→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    45→\n    46→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    47→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    48→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    49→reassignment.\n    50→\n    51→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    52→file is a parse error.\n    53→\n    54→## Concepts\n    55→\n    56→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    57→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    58→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    59→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    60→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    61→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    62→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    63→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    64→\n    65→## Step Types\n    66→\n    67→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    68→\n    69→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    70→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    71→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    72→\n    73→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    74→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    75→\n    76→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    77→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    78→\n    79→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    80→parse error.\n    81→\n    82→## DSL Syntax\n    83→\n    84→```\n    85→workflow \"develop\" {\n    86→  container {\n    87→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    88→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step implement {\n    92→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step test {\n    97→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    98→    results = [success, fail]\n    99→  }\n   100→\n   101→  step fix {\n   102→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   103→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n   104→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   105→  }\n   106→\n   107→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   108→  implement:success -> test\n   109→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   110→  test:success      -> done\n   111→  test:fail         -> fix\n   112→  fix:success       -> test\n   113→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   114→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   115→}\n   116→```\n   117→\n   118→## Key Properties\n   119→\n   120→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   121→field makes it a script step.\n   122→\n   123→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   124→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   125→\n   126→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   127→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   128→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   129→\n   130→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   131→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   132→\n   133→## Wire Output Mappings\n   134→\n   135→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   136→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   137→\n   138→```\n   139→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   140→```\n   141→\n   142→The general form:\n   143→\n   144→```\n   145→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   149→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   150→\n   151→| Expression | Meaning |\n   152→|---|---|\n   153→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   154→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   155→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   156→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   157→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   158→\n   159→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   160→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   161→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   162→\n   163→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   164→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   165→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   166→\n   167→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   168→\n   169→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   170→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   171→\n   172→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   173→network allowlist.\n   174→\n   175→```\n   176→workflow \"develop\" {\n   177→  container {\n   178→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   179→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   180→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   181→  }\n   182→  ...\n   183→}\n   184→```\n   185→\n   186→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   187→\n   188→**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   189→running on the host machine.\n   190→\n   191→```\n   192→workflow \"main\" {\n   193→  host {\n   194→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   195→  }\n   196→  ...\n   197→}\n   198→```\n   199→\n   200→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   201→\n   202→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   203→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   204→var > default `claude`.\n   205→\n   206→## Host Workflow Example\n   207→\n   208→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   209→workflows:\n   210→\n   211→```\n   212→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   213→\n   214→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   215→  step fetch-tickets {\n   216→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   217→    results = [success, fail]\n   218→  }\n   219→\n   220→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   221→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   222→}\n   223→\n   224→workflow \"main\" {\n   225→  host {\n   226→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  step prepare-prompt {\n   230→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   231→    results = [success, fail]\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  step develop {\n   235→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   236→    results       = [success, fail]\n   237→  }\n   238→\n   239→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   240→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   241→  develop:success        -> done\n   242→  develop:fail           -> done\n   243→}\n   244→\n   245→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   246→  step push-for-review {\n   247→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   248→    results = [success, fail]\n   249→  }\n   250→\n   251→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   252→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   253→}\n   254→```\n   255→\n   256→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   257→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   258→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   259→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   260→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   261→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   262→\n   263→## Execution Model\n   264→\n   265→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   266→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   267→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   268→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   269→\n   270→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   271→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   272→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   273→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   274→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   275→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   276→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   277→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   278→points to the actual project directory.\n   279→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01X39tUhxFjzAhiJaof3xvLs","session_id":"80e1ce2e-a764-409e-b43f-733763e5218d","uuid":"4d68e10d-9ac7-40c2-872f-1f348ac18c1b"}
